description: This red ear sunfish was caught in a seine net in Lanana creek in Nacogdoches, Texas. It was 90 degrees Fahrenheit and 58% humidity. The wind was blowing SW at 9 mph. Vegetation near the edges of the creek was thick and abundant.

I saw this species in the water at Sweetwater preserve about mid day. They were close to the surface of the water possible looking for bugs floating on the top. I identified them in Family Centrarchidae because they are entirely fresh-water fish and they are characterized by their symmetrically-shaped body, rather short and compressed. They have a terminal mouth and a single dorsal fin comprised of both spiny and soft rays and an anal fin with both spiny and soft rays.
